---
import MarketingLayout from "../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="MailAtlas: Local Email Infrastructure for Agents and Data Apps"
  description="MailAtlas turns email into inspectable local data. Ingest messages from files or IMAP, export structured documents, and send provider-backed email with a local audit trail."
>
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
      <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <span>MailAtlas</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="topnav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="#why">Why</a>
      <a href="#sources">Sources</a>
      <a href="#stores">Stored data</a>
      <a href="/docs/">Docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="landing-main">
    <section class="hero" id="overview">
      <div class="hero-artifact" aria-hidden="true">
        <span>Subject:</span>
        <span>From: alice@example.com</span>
        <span>$ mailatlas ingest</span>
        <span>Content-Type: text/html</span>
        <span>attachment.pdf</span>
        <span>Message-ID:</span>
        <span>mbox://archive.2024</span>
        <span>outbound/raw</span>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Open-source email infrastructure</p>
        <h1>Make email usable as local data.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          MailAtlas ingests email from files and selected IMAP folders into a local workspace you
          can inspect from the CLI, Python, or MCP-compatible tools. Each document stays linked to
          its raw source, HTML, attachments, metadata, and exports, so software can search, review,
          and process email without scraping a web inbox.
        </p>
        <p class="lede lede-tight">
          For outbound workflows, MailAtlas can render a message, store a local audit record, and
          send through a configured provider.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Primary actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Start with files</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions hero-actions-secondary" aria-label="Secondary actions">
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Connect IMAP</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Configure sending</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">View GitHub</a>
        </div>
        <p class="hero-command"><code>python -m pip install mailatlas</code></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="why">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Why MailAtlas</p>
        <h2>Email is useful application data, but inboxes were built for people.</h2>
        <p>
          Email can contain plain text, HTML, inline images, attachments, forwarded chains, delivery
          headers, provider metadata, and context that matters later. If an application flattens all
          of that into text, it loses structure. If it relies on a mailbox UI, the workflow is hard
          to inspect, test, or automate reliably.
        </p>
        <p>
          MailAtlas stores email as local artifacts plus structured metadata. Your application can
          use the cleaned representation when that is enough, then fall back to raw messages, HTML
          snapshots, attachments, and parser notes when it needs more context.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Use MailAtlas when you need to</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Build an email corpus for retrieval, analytics, AI agent workflows, or audits.</li>
            <li>Keep raw messages, cleaned text, HTML, attachments, and metadata linked together.</li>
            <li>Process <code>.eml</code> files or <code>mbox</code> archives without running a hosted service.</li>
            <li>Fetch selected IMAP folders into a local workspace.</li>
            <li>Send email through configured providers while keeping a local audit trail.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="story">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
        <h2>One workspace for inbound mail, exports, and outbound records.</h2>
      </div>

      <ol class="step-list">
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Ingest or sync messages</h3>
            <p>
              Start from <code>.eml</code> files, an <code>mbox</code> archive, or selected folders
              in an IMAP mailbox. File ingest is useful for local fixtures, archives, tests, and
              one-off processing. Manual IMAP sync is useful when messages still live in a mailbox.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Store linked artifacts</h3>
            <p>
              MailAtlas stores the raw message, cleaned text, normalized HTML, extracted assets,
              source metadata, and parser notes together. The stored document remains traceable back
              to the input that produced it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Inspect, export, or build</h3>
            <p>
              Use the CLI, Python API, or MCP server to list documents, inspect a message, export
              JSON, Markdown, HTML, or PDF, or connect the workspace to your own workflow.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">04</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Send with an audit trail</h3>
            <p>
              For outbound email, MailAtlas can render the message, copy attachments, store local
              audit records, and send through SMTP, Cloudflare Email Service, or Gmail API OAuth.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="sources">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Sources and sinks</p>
        <h2>Choose the path that matches your email source.</h2>
        <p>
          Start with one path and add others later. File ingest, IMAP sync, exports, and outbound
          sends all operate against the same local workspace.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Files</strong>
          <span>
            Use file ingest when you already have individual <code>.eml</code> files, directories
            of exported messages, or test fixtures.
          </span>
          <code>.eml</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/examples/mbox-ingest/">
          <strong>Archive</strong>
          <span>
            Use <code>mbox</code> ingest when you have a mailbox export on disk and want each
            message stored as a document.
          </span>
          <code>mbox</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Mailbox</strong>
          <span>
            Use manual IMAP sync when messages still live in a mailbox and you want to fetch
            selected folders on demand.
          </span>
          <code>sync</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>
            Use outbound email when your application needs to render, store, send, and audit
            messages through a configured provider.
          </span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="try">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Try it</p>
        <h2>Verify the workflow with one message.</h2>
        <p>Start with a local workspace, ingest one message, then list the stored document.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="terminal">
        <div class="terminal-bar">
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <code>~/work</code>
        </div>
        <pre><code>python3.12 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
python -m pip install mailatlas

export MAILATLAS_HOME="$PWD/.mailatlas"
mailatlas ingest path/to/message.eml
mailatlas list</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="terminal terminal-secondary">
        <div class="terminal-bar">
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <code>sample fixtures</code>
        </div>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/mailatlas/sample-data.git
mailatlas ingest sample-data/fixtures/eml/atlas-market-map.eml
mailatlas list</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="stores">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">What MailAtlas stores</p>
        <h2>Local files, SQLite metadata, and provider-safe audit records.</h2>
        <p>
          MailAtlas writes ordinary local artifacts into a workspace root and uses SQLite for lookup,
          dedupe, sync state, and outbound records.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list storage-list">
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Inbound</strong>
          <span>Original raw email bytes, cleaned body text, normalized HTML snapshots, and metadata.</span>
          <code>raw/ html/ store.db</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Assets</strong>
          <span>Extracted inline images and regular file attachments associated with a document.</span>
          <code>assets</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Exports</strong>
          <span>JSON, Markdown, HTML, and PDF artifacts written from stored documents.</span>
          <code>exports/</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Mailbox sync</strong>
          <span>IMAP sync cursors for manual selected-folder sync.</span>
          <code>store.db</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>
            Outbound <code>.eml</code> snapshots, body files, copied attachments, recipient metadata,
            provider status, error details, and retry metadata.
          </span>
          <code>outbound/ store.db</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="section-note">
        Provider credentials are read at runtime. MailAtlas does not write SMTP passwords,
        Cloudflare API tokens, IMAP passwords, Gmail tokens, or OAuth access tokens into the
        workspace database, raw snapshots, logs, or JSON send results.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-fit" id="fit">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Is MailAtlas for you?</p>
        <h2>Use it when local email artifacts matter. Use something else for hosted mail products.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Reach for MailAtlas when</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You are feeding email into an AI agent, retrieval system, notebook, test suite, or data app.</li>
            <li>You need raw, cleaned, structured, and visual views of the same message.</li>
            <li>You want to script over <code>.eml</code> files or <code>mbox</code> archives without a hosted service.</li>
            <li>You need selected-folder IMAP sync into a local store.</li>
            <li>You need a local audit trail for email your application sends.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article>
          <h3>Use something else when</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You need a hosted inbox product or full webmail client.</li>
            <li>You need background mailbox sync as a managed service.</li>
            <li>You need deliverability management, campaign analytics, suppression lists, bounce processing, or marketing automation.</li>
            <li>You only need a low-level MIME parser and do not care about storage, exports, or provenance.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="next">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Next steps</p>
        <h2>Pick the first workflow you need to prove.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/installation/">
          <strong>Install MailAtlas</strong>
          <span>Set up the CLI and verify the install with <code>mailatlas doctor</code>.</span>
          <code>install</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Run the Quickstart</strong>
          <span>Ingest a local <code>.eml</code> file and export a stored document.</span>
          <code>files</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Sync a mailbox folder</strong>
          <span>Fetch selected IMAP folders into the same local workspace.</span>
          <code>imap</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Configure sending</strong>
          <span>Render, store, and send messages through a configured provider.</span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer-cta">
      <div class="footer-brand">
        <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>MailAtlas</span>
        </a>
        <p>MailAtlas is open-source email infrastructure for local workspaces. Read the docs, install it, and keep your mail where you can inspect it.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <nav class="footer-links" aria-label="Footer">
        <div>
          <h2>Docs</h2>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Quickstart</a>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Manual IMAP Sync</a>
          <a href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Outbound Email</a>
          <a href="/docs/concepts/workspace-model/">Workspace Model</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Project</h2>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/examples">Examples</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/sample-data">Sample Data</a>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/roadmap/">Roadmap</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Trust</h2>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/security-and-privacy/">Security and Privacy</a>
          <a href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas/issues">Issues</a>
        </div>
      </nav>

      <div class="footer-bottom">
        <span>© 2026 MailAtlas. MIT licensed.</span>
        <span>local-first</span>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </main>
</MarketingLayout>
